# code-quality-bot-ignores-noqa — History

## v1.2.0 (2026-07-05) — Triage patterns: PEP-562 `__all__` lazy exports + PEP-544 Protocol `...`

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PR #1851 (epic #1809 pipeline package)
**Verification:** verified-local (the triage + code fixes were applied and gated locally this
session; the merge/CI-green confirmation was pending at capture time). Prior verified-ci content retained.

### What changed
- Added the **`__all__`-lazy-export triage pattern**: github-code-quality[bot] flags PEP-562
  lazy-export names (`__all__` names bound via a module-level `def __getattr__(name)`, per ADR-0002)
  as "exported by __all__ but is not defined." This CAN be a false positive (name resolvable via
  `__getattr__` → refute + resolve) OR a REAL bug (name has no lazy backing → `from pkg import X`
  raises `ImportError` → fix `__all__` or add the lazy branch). On #1851 two names were real gaps →
  fixed by wiring the missing `__getattr__` branches.
- Added the **`[getattr(pkg,n) for n in pkg.__all__]` acceptance oracle** —
  `python -c "import pkg; [getattr(pkg, n) for n in pkg.__all__]"` must succeed for every exported
  name. It exercises the lazy path, unlike a static grep, so it robustly distinguishes false
  positive from genuine bug.
- Added the **Protocol `...` "statement has no effect" false-positive** shape: PEP-544 Protocol
  methods with `...` bodies on `stages/base.py` are flagged "This statement has no effect"; it is
  ALWAYS a false positive (cross-references sibling skill `python-protocol-stub-ellipsis-not-pass`).
  Do NOT "fix" it by switching to `pass`.
- Added the **duplicate-assignment genuine-finding contrast** (`exit_code` dead store) to reinforce
  that not every bot thread is a false positive.
- Added a "Triaging bot findings: false-positive vs genuine" subsection under Verified Workflow, a
  new Failed Attempts row (blanket-resolving all threads missed two REAL `__all__` gaps), a
  "Verified On" row for PR #1851, and extended the `description` "Use when" list.
- **Key generalization:** github-code-quality[bot] does static, diff-scoped analysis that does NOT
  understand PEP 562 lazy exports or PEP 544 Protocol stubs. Findings must be TRIAGED individually —
  the resolve-via-GraphQL remedy applies only to confirmed false positives; genuine findings must be
  fixed in code.

### Why
The same bot produced two finding shapes not covered by v1.1.0 (`__all__`-export-not-defined on a
PEP-562 lazy-export package; Protocol `...` statement-has-no-effect), plus a genuine dead-store
finding. Critically, the `__all__` shape is NOT uniformly a false positive — two names were real
runtime `ImportError` gaps — so the skill needed an explicit triage rule and an acceptance oracle to
avoid the failure mode of blanket-resolving genuine findings.

### Full snapshot of the PREVIOUS v1.1.0 skill body

```markdown
---
name: code-quality-bot-ignores-noqa
description: "GitHub's `github-code-quality[bot]` static analyzer flags imports as 'unused' even when they have explicit `# noqa: F401` markers, blocking PR merge under org rulesets with `required_review_thread_resolution`. The fix isn't to fight the bot or rewrite the imports — it's to resolve the threads via `gh api graphql resolveReviewThread` with one explanatory PR comment. Use when: (1) bot review comments flag deliberate test-patch-seam re-exports as 'unused imports', (2) PR shows `MERGEABLE / BLOCKED` with all CI checks green, (3) `required_review_thread_resolution` is in the org ruleset."
category: tooling
date: 2026-05-28
version: "1.1.0"
user-invocable: false
verification: verified-ci
history: code-quality-bot-ignores-noqa.history
tags: [github, pull-request, code-quality, review-threads, noqa]
